Mortgage: The minimum, 25th percentile and median values are all 0, which means that at least half of the customers don't have a mortgage. The distribution is highly right-skewed, having a lot of 0s (no mortgage) and a long tail to higher mortgage values for those who do have a mortgage.

Conclusions:

Both 'Age' and 'Experience' appear to have distributions that are almost uniform. The bars for 'Age' are relatively even between 30 and 60, and for 'Experience' between 10 and 30.

'Income' shows a positively skewed distribution. Most of the income values are concentrated at the lower end (around 50-70), with a long tail extending towards higher income values.

'Mortgage's distribution is highly right-skewed. There is a peak at 0, indicating that many customers don't have a mortgage. The tail represents a smaller number of customers with large mortgage amounts.

'CCAvg's distribution is also highly right-skewed. It suggests that a large concentration of customers spend very little, while a long tail represents a smaller number of individuals who spend more.

The correlation coefficient between 'Age' and 'Personal_Loan' is -0.01, which is extremely low. Therefore, there doesn't seem to be a correlation between the age of the customers and the likelihood of them taking on a loan or not.

'Age': The median age is 45 years. The IQR ranges from 35 to 55 years, indicating that 50% of the customers fall within this age bracket. There are no outliers. Both distributions (with personal loan and without) are very similar, suggesting that 'Age' is not a strong factor.

'Experience': The median is around 20 years. The IQR ranges from about 10 to 30 years. No outliers. Again, very similar distributions, thus weak correlation between 'Experience' and 'Personal_Loan'.

'Income': The median income is around 60 for the customers without a personal loan and around 140 for the customers with a personal loan. Customers with a personal loan have a higher median income as well as a higher distribution. Looking back at the correlation matrix, 'Income' was the highest correlation [0.50].

'CCAvg': Customers with a personal loan have a higher average on credit card spendings. For non-loan customers, the median is around 1.0-1.5, while for loan customers the median is higher, around 3.0-4.0. Their correlation coefficient is [0.37] which is already significant.

Mortgage: For customers who do not have a personal loan, the median Mortgage value is 0, indicating a large proportion with no mortgage. For customers with a personal loan, the median is around 150-200. This suggests that customers with a mortgage are more likely to take on a personal loan, though the overall correlation is only [0.14], indicating a weak relationship.

As a result, it seems that 'Income' and 'CCAvg' are good indicators of being able to take or not a personal loan: when they increase, the customers are more likely to take on a personal loan.

Detect outliers

In[109]:
numerical_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']).columns

outlier_counts = {}

for col in numerical_cols:
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    outliers = df[(df[col] < lower) | (df[col] > upper)]
    outlier_counts[col] = len(outliers)

outlier_counts = pd.Series(outlier_counts).sort_values(ascending=False)
print(outlier_counts)

In[115]:
# post-pruning

clf_full = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)
clf_full.fit(X_train, y_train)

path = clf_full.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, y_train)
ccp_alphas = path.ccp_alphas
impurities = path.impurities

clfs = []
for ccp_alpha in ccp_alphas:
    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42, ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha)
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    clfs.append(clf)

f1_scores = [f1_score(y_test, clf.predict(X_test)) for clf in clfs]

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(ccp_alphas, f1_scores, marker='o')
plt.xlabel("ccp_alpha")
plt.ylabel("F1 Score")
plt.title("F1 Score vs CCP Alpha for Post-Pruning")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

clf_postpruned = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42, ccp_alpha=0.005)
clf_postpruned.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Pruned Tree Depth:", clf_postpruned.get_depth())
print("Pruned Tree Leaves:", clf_postpruned.get_n_leaves())

Pruned Tree Depth: 3
Pruned Tree Leaves: 5

Conclusion:

F1 score seems to be higher at the top left of the chart. Setting ccp_alpha to 0.005 is a good choice because it reduces the trees complexity and avoids overfitting.

print("Recall:", recall_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("F1 Score:", f1_score(y_test, y_pred))

plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
plot_tree(clf_postpruned, filled=True, feature_names=X_train.columns, class_names=["No", "Yes"], max_depth=3)
plt.title("Post-Pruned Decision Tree")
plt.show()

Accuracy: 0.9793333333333333
Precision: 0.9701492537313433
Recall: 0.8280254777070064
F1 Score: 0.8934707903780069

Conclusion:

The post-pruned tree is simpler, with a depth of 3 and 5 leaves.

It has a high accuracy (97.9%) and precision (97%), resulting in few false positives.

Recall (83%) has worsen a bit though.

F1 (0.89) is a high number.

Model Performance Comparison and Final Model Selection

Conclusion:

The Banks goal is to increase the number of customers as rapidly as possible, so the most important metrics are:

  • Recall: Relates to True Positives; the Bank wants to identify as many potential loan takers as possible. A high recall is very important.
  • Precision: Measures how many of the Predicted Positives are actually True Positives. The higher it is, the more efficient it is for the Marketing team.
  • F1 Score: A balance between Precision and Recall.

Both the second pruned tree and the post-pruned tree display good metrics. However, the second pruned tree displays higher Recall, Accuracy and F1 Score. Because the Bank wants to target as many potential customers as possible and Recall helps with identifying them, Recall aligns well with this goal.

The second pruned tree is more complex but it is still simpler than the original tree.

  1. The Bank should focus on high-education and high-income customers as these two are the most important features in the model. Customers with 'Graduate' or 'Professional' levels are more likely to take on a personal loan.

  1. Bigger families are more likely to accept personal loans. As such, promoting deals that benefit families with children would be beneficial.
